# Angular Architecture Conventions

## Standalone Components (No NgModules)

```typescript
// BAD
@Component({ selector: 'app-user' })
export class UserComponent {}

@NgModule({ declarations: [UserComponent] })
export class UserModule {}
```

```typescript
// GOOD
@Component({
  selector: 'app-user',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [],
})
export class UserComponent {}
```

- New components must be `standalone: true`.
- Do not create feature-level `NgModule` wrappers.

## Reactive State with Signals

```typescript
// BAD
private user$ = new BehaviorSubject<User | null>(null);
```

```typescript
// GOOD
private user = signal<User | null>(null);
userReadonly = this.user.asReadonly();
```

- Use `signal()` as the default local reactive state primitive.
- Expose read-only state with `.asReadonly()` when needed.

## Dependency Injection with `inject()`

```typescript
// BAD
constructor(private http: HttpClient, private router: Router) {}
```

```typescript
// GOOD
private http = inject(HttpClient);
private router = inject(Router);
```

- Prefer property-based DI via `inject()` over constructor parameter injection.

## Project Folder Structure

- `features/`: domain features (components, routes, state, facades).
- `shared/`: reusable UI, pipes, directives, utilities.
- `core/`: singletons, app-wide services, interceptors, guards.

When creating or refactoring Angular code, always follow these conventions.
